{"title":"In the Drops: Super wide Pirelli tyres, featherweight Alpitude saddle, smart Lezyne lights and a natty Feedback Sports tool","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/pirelli-p-zero-race-tlr-tyres","date":1737115741000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/pirelli-p-zero-race-tlr-tyres\">In the Drops: Super wide Pirelli tyres, featherweight Alpitude saddle, smart Lezyne lights and a natty Feedback Sports tool</a></p>\n\n<p>It feels like the cycling world has properly woken up for 2025 this week. The <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/giro-ditalia-watch-live-stages-route-riders-teams-start-list\" target=\"_blank\">Giro d’Italia route has been revealed</a> and talk has turned to the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/womens-tour-down-under-preview\" target=\"_blank\">Tour Down Under</a>, plus new products, such as the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/basso-sv-2025\" target=\"_blank\">new Basso SV</a> and <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/p/DE4eZzEux3m/?img_index=1\" target=\"_blank\">Ridley’s wild new Noah Fast</a>, are starting to launch. Considering the quantity of emails about embargoed products filling my inbox, there’s no doubt this is only the beginning as well.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Even though the reactive articles are starting to ramp up, we’ve maintained our more timeless output as well this week, with a feature on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tutorials/strength-training-for-cyclists\" target=\"_blank\">weight and strength training for cyclists</a>, as well as how tos on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tutorials/how-to-clean-bike-helmet\" target=\"_blank\">cleaning bike helmets</a> and <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/bike-tyre-pressure\" target=\"_blank\">choosing the right tyre pressure</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The latest edition of <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/in-the-drops\" target=\"_blank\">In the Drops</a> is only the first piece of content going online today as well, so be sure to check back throughout the day to keep up to date.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n<h2>Pirelli P Zero Race TLR 40mm tyres</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Pirelli bicycle tyres\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-5.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption>Sam Challis</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It doesn’t seem so long ago that 28mm slick tyres were considered wide, but the latest road tyre designs being added to brands’ ranges stretch to 40mm and above. Pirelli’s new P Zero Race TLR is an excellent example, combining gravel tyre volume with a slick road tread (though it’s worth noting that Pirelli hasn’t just sized up from its normal Race TLR range, but bulked up the construction of the 40mm variant as well).</p>\n\n\n\n<p>‘To a large extent, several of wide tyres’ benefits for road riders – comfort, grip, etc – just keep increasing with width, but we see the use-case for our new 40mm Pirelli P-Zero Race TLR as road-ifying gravel bikes,’ says Pirelli’s Samuele Bressan. ‘Many gravel bikes, particularly the racier ones, can be made to feel like road bikes, but putting traditional road tyres on affects the geometry.’</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Pirelli bicycle tyres\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-6.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption>Sam Challis</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The geometry of gravel bikes is designed around big tyres, which raise the frame off the ground more than road tyres would. Importantly, aspects such as trail – which governs the bike’s response to steering input – and bottom bracket height might be affected by slotting in narrower tyres, as that effectively lowers the bike. It might not handle as stably or be more at risk of pedal-strike when cornering.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>‘The extra width of our 40mm P Zeros gives the necessary tyre volume to preserve the bike’s geometry, but the slick tread allows road-like speed,’ says Bressan. ‘Thanks to all that volume, there’s also huge scope to play with tyre pressure: drop it down for extra cushion on rougher routes, or pump it up for a faster ride feel on the tarmac.’</p>\n\n\n\n<div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/subscriptions?utm_source=Web&amp;utm_medium=Banner&amp;utm_campaign=Banner+4\" target=\"_blank\"><img width=\"970\" height=\"300\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-4-970x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-4-970x300.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-4-300x93.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-4-768x238.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-4-1536x476.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-4-2048x634.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-4-750x232.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-4-1140x353.jpg 1140w\" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>Alpitude Navene saddle</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Alpitude bike saddle\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-10.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption>Sam Challis</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In search of some extra exotic finishing components to complete a dream build? You need not look any further than Alpitude. The boutique company makes all of its products in its facility nestled in the Dolomites.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>‘I started Alpitude in 2015 with the goal of making custom framesets, but the finishing parts of the business took off when I made the market’s first carbon fibre computer mount,’ says CEO Andrea Sega.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Given how many small parts a bike includes, Alpitude’s range has expanded over the years – it now features products such as chain catchers, top caps, bottle cages and even oversized derailleur cages – but Sega says he still rather that brand focus is on quality over quantity.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>‘Focussing on a limited product range has given us the opportunity to really specialise, making products like the new Navene saddle possible,’ he says.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Alpitude bike saddle\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-12.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption>Sam Challis</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The Navene saddle weighs just 72g, despite Sega saying it’s robust enough for off-road use.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>‘We apply forces far higher than ISO standards dictate,’ says Sega. ‘The saddle has been developed over three years with pro riders. It has allowed us to define how to lay up the carbon to make the saddle strong but also flex where required so that it’s comfortable.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>‘Most of a saddle’s comfort comes from its shape anyway, so we’ve blended ergonomic features such as a central cut-out and short nose to make sure the rider can drop significant weight off their bike without compromise.’</p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Find out more about the Alpitude Navene saddle at <a href=\"https://alpitude.cc/navene-carbon-saddle/\" target=\"_blank\">alpitude.cc</a></strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/all-work-and-no-play-2\">All work and no play part 2: The women’s peloton is walking the tightrope</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/basso-sv-2025\">New Basso SV all-round road bike replaces aero Diamante SV</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/mens-tour-down-under-preview\">Men’s Tour Down Under 2025 preview: Route, favourites, how to watch and start list</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/womens-tour-down-under-preview\">Women’s Tour Down Under 2025: Route, how to watch and start list</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/bike-tyre-pressure\">Bike tyre pressure guide: How to choose the best pressure</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<h2>Lezyne Lite Drive 1200+ and Ai Alert 250 light set</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Lezyne front and rear bike lights\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-7.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption>Sam Challis</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The Lite Drive 1200+ may look like the headline act here, and in a sense it is, with a huge 1,200-lumen maximum output despite a long 60-hour maximum run time, but it’s the diminutive Ai Alert 250 that really steals the show.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>‘The light uses AI to more accurately detect deceleration and accordingly adjust its light pattern versus the accelerometers found in other lights,’ says brand manager Mark Robinson. ‘Our Ai lights were developed after recording and analysing thousands of hours of riding data from bikes equipped with specialised sensors, and enhance rider safety.’</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Lezyne front and rear bike lights\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-9.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption>Sam Challis</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>That’s all packed into a small and light package as well, but the taillight still offers 270° visibility and the same 60-hour maximum runtime as its bulkier partner up front.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Lezyne Lite Drive 1200+</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Lezyne Ai Alert 250</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<h2>Feedback Sports Reflex Fixed Torque Bit Driver</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Feedback multitool\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-2.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption>Sam Challis</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>There are some excellent conventional multitools on the market, but the form factor of most leaves plenty to be desired in the ergonomics stakes. Of the ones that are comfortable to use, fewer still offer the ability to achieve known torque values. Feedback Sports aims to add to that rarefied list with its Reflex Fixed Torque Bit Driver.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The nylon body sits as snugly in the hand as its compact form does in a saddlebag. Unscrewing the knurled, anodised cap reveals chambers for four bits (4, 5, 6mm Hex and T25 Torx bits are supplied as standard) and one 5Nm preset torque collar.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Feedback multitool\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/in-the-drops-17-01-25-3.jpg 2000w\" /><figcaption>Sam Challis</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Slip the collar into the port on the body, fix the required bit into the collar and you’ll have a nicely made and functional T-handle torque driver that should see you right for most common adjustments.</p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Find out more about the Feedback Sports Reflex Fixed Torque Bit Driver at <a href=\"https://saddleback.co.uk/products/feedback-sports-reflex-fixed-torque-bit-driver?srsltid=AfmBOop03cV1Kmv76C0s1625JW1tBhJCM_jDVoCZ22fCiPfycWdDiGaS\" target=\"_blank\">saddleback.co.uk</a></strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/newsletters\" target=\"_blank\"><img width=\"970\" height=\"351\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-4-970x351.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-4-970x351.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-4-300x109.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-4-768x278.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-4-1536x556.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-4-2048x741.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-4-750x271.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-4-1140x412.jpg 1140w\" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/pirelli-p-zero-race-tlr-tyres\">In the Drops: Super wide Pirelli tyres, featherweight Alpitude saddle, smart Lezyne lights and a natty Feedback Sports tool</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"Sam Challis &#124; Tech Editor","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"422d578cd43521c228768b32de90a396ba45e89bd4e1cb8ea89b6630a2b087e0","category":"Cycling"}